vely with others” alberts is also noted as one of the original authors of the molecular biology of the cell a preeminent textbook in the field soon to be in its sixth edition for the period  to  he served as the cochair of the interacademy council a new organization in amsterdam governed by the presidents of  national academies of sciences and established to provide scientific advice to the world committed in his international work to the promotion of the “creativity openness and tolerance that are inherent to science” alberts believes that “scientists all around the world must now band together to help create more rational scientificallybased societies that find dogmatism intolerable” widely recognized for his work in the fields of biochemistry and molecular biology alberts has earned many honors and awards including  honorary degrees he currently serves on the advisory boards of more than  nonprofit institutions including the gordon and betty moore foundation view dr alberts’ curriculum vitae   last updated september   at  pm home about current projects previous work writings photo galleries videos interviews talks contact   test bank for molecular biology of the cell th edition test bank  bruce alberts  skip to navigation skip to content search for   items test bank for molecular biology of the cell th edition test bank – bruce alberts  add to cart sku  tags bank test th alberts biology bruce cell edition molecular molecular biology of the cell th edition test bank  bruce alberts of the description reviews  product description molecular biology of the cell th edition test bank – bruce alberts chapter  dna chromosomes and genomes molecular biology of the cell fifth edition   garland science publishing questions  figure q shows a hypothetical alignment of nucleotide sequences from two organisms the bottom panel shows an alignment of large chromosomal regions with black blocks representing dna stretches of at least  nucleotides for which there is a corresponding sequence somewhere in the other organism’s genome gray lines connect the pairs of corresponding sequences found in this alignment region the top panel shows a magnified view of one region approximately the length of an average gene here each vertical gray line represents a stretch of six nucleotides in which five of the six are identical between the two species annotate the top panel of the figure to indicate likely locations of exons introns and regulatory sequences annotate the bottom panel to show regions of synteny figure q  the dynamics of nucleosomes can be studied in a test tube by mixing histone proteins with short pieces of dna to form a single nucleosome on each dna molecule when a dye molecule is covalently linked to one end of the dna and a complementary dye molecule is linked to a histone protein the proximity of the two dyes can be measured such measurements combined with other experiments suggested that nucleosomes alternated between two states one fully wrapped w and the second partly unwrapped u the equilibrium constant between these two states keq  uw depends on the concentration of salt in the test tube at the salt concentration found in cells the keq was between  and  a about what percentage of the time is a given nucleosome partly unwrapped at this salt concentration explain b will increasing the salt concentration increase or decrease the keq explain  when placed on an agar slab and incubated at °c for  days a single yeast cell proliferates into a colony with a diameter of  mm containing  yeast cells if the cell has a functional ade gene ade the colony will be white if ade is nonfunctional ade– the colony will be red you take a strain with a mutant ade– at the regular chromosomal position red colonies and insert a second functional ade gene near the telomere you find that the colonies are a mixture of red and white patches or sectors figure q shows some colonies the black regions represent the red sectors a explain what happened to the ade gene near the telomere in the red cells and in the white cells what is the term for this phenomenon b you take single cells from the white sectors and allow them to form new colonies you do the same with cells from the red sectors predict the color of the colonies explain c you measure acetylation of the ntermini of histones h and h that are located near the telomeric ade do you expect more or less acetylation in the red cells than in the white cells d you look for mutants that give only white colonies you find mutations in three genes rap which encodes a protein that binds specific short dna sequences near the telomere sir which encodes a histone deacetlyase and sir which encodes a protein that binds rap sir and deacetylated ntermini of histones h and h propose a series of events in which these proteins act together to turn a white cell into a red cell figure q  you want to examine where within the cell a protein called tip resides to do this you make a dna construct containing regulatory sequences rs that control gene expression the proteincoding region of the tip gene and a sequence that codes for green fluorescent protein gfp the expressed fusion protein includes the tip protein covalently linked at one end to gfp and therefore you can visualize the subcellular location of tip by viewing green fluorescence with a microscope you transfect mouse cells with the rstipgfp construct and find cells in which the constructs have been inserted in the genome at random you look at  colonies each arising from an independent insertion and find that some colonies contain cells that all have high levels of fluorescence whereas other colonies have only cells with moderate or low levels two colonies even have a mixture of cells some with high levels of fluorescence and others with low levels a explain the observed differences between colonies and for each observed colony behavior b propose an improved version of your rstipgfp construct that might make the colonies more uniform list the order of sequences in the improved construct  you want to investigate the substructure of an intact interphase nucleus to do this you fix cells and isolate their nuclei you add fluorescent antibodies that bind specifically to particular proteins and then observe fluorescence with a microscope a nucleus is represented in figure q which of the proteins listed below do you expect to be concentrated in a subnuclear region indicate on the figure where you expect those proteins to localize proteins hp histone h acetylated on lysine  histone h methylated on lysine  histone h and condensin figure q  gene duplication is widely believed to be a major mechanism for generating genetic novelty and increased biological complexity a how does a pseudogene arise b identify the simplest kind of experiment to begin characterizing the divergence of a pair of functional genes that arose from an ancient duplication event and describe what results are expected c because of the availability of wholegenome dna sequences and wholegenome gene expression measurements researchers classify each gene as a member of a duplicated set or a singleton and then evaluate whether there is a difference between expression patterns of the two classes which class contains a larger proportion of genes whose expression differs between strains of an organism which class contains a larger proportion of genes whose expression differs between different stages in embryogenesis explain  a hypothetical phylogenetic tree is shown in figure q use this tree to answer the following questions a how many years ago did species m and n diverge from their last common ancestor b how much nucleotide divergence is there on average between m and n c are m and n more or less closely related to each other than p and s d in looking for functionally important nucleotide sequences is it more informative to compare the genome sequences of m and n or those of m and q explain figure q  consider a gene with a particular function mutation x and mutation y separately cause defects in the function of the encoded protein yet a gene containing both mutations x and y encodes a protein that works even better than the original protein the odds that a single mutational event will generate both mutations x and y are exceedingly small explain a simple way in which an organism with a mutant gene containing both mutations x and y could arise during evolution answers  figure a  a the percentage of the time is – an equilibrium constant between  and  means that at a given instant – of the nucleosomes are partly unwrapped because the question said that each nucleosome alternates between the two states the previous sentence can be transformed to say that a single nucleosome spends – of the time in a partly unwrapped state b increase a higher salt concentration will disrupt the nucleosomes because they are held together largely by ionic interactions between the positively charged histone proteins and the negatively charged dna this will lead to more unwrapped nucleosomes and fewer wrapped nucleosomes which will increase the keq reference li g widom j  nucleosomes facilitate their own invasion natstruct mol biol  –  a in the white cells the inserted ade gene is expressed and the ade protein is made in the red cells the inserted ade gene has undergone gene silencing probably as a result of spreading of heterochromatin from the telomere this is called positioneffect variegation b the cells from both colors of sectors will generate new colonies that are also sectored colonies from red cells may tend to have more red than white colonies from white cells may have more white than red the ade gene in white cells is probably packaged in euchromatin and in red cells in heterochromatin the chromatin state of a genomic locus is often directly inherited during the process of dna replication causing a phenomenon called epigenetic inheritance so red white cells will tend to make more red white cells but with positioneffect variegation there is a certain low frequency of switching of chromatin from a repressed to an expressed state and vice versa so red white cells can become white red c more histone acetylation will occur near the telomeric ade in the cells that actively express the gene that is in the white cells expressed regions of the genome are enriched in acetylated histones d a white cell is turned into a red cell by spreading of heterochromatin from the telomere to the ade inserted nearby the spreading might happen as follows  rap binds a site in the telomeric region  sir binds to rap and recruits sir  sir deacetylates histones near rap  more sir binds to the deacetylated histones and recruits more sir  sir deacetylates more histones farther from the rapbinding site  repeat steps  and  for many cycles in a chain reaction until the deacetylation reaches the ade gene deacetylated histones are components of heterochromatin and they may recruit other histonemodifying enzymes histonebinding proteins and chromatinremodeling complexes  a the differences between the colonies probably arise from position effects the construct might have inserted near sequence elements and chromatin structures that enhance gene expression high fluorescence have no effect on gene expression high or moderate fluorescence repress gene expression low fluorescence or spread heterochromatin into the inserted construct variable fluorescence the colonies with mixed populations of cells probably contain the construct inserted near heterochromatin which spreads into the construct in some cells but not others b the construct might confer more uniform gene expression independently of where it inserted in the genome if it contained barrier sequences barrier sequences like hs from the chicken betaglobin locus normally separate an active chromatin domain from a silenced chromatin domain barrier sequences bss can insulate a dna construct from position effects if they flank the important sequences on both sides an improved construct containing bsrstipgfpbs might yield more uniform expression among and within the colonies  see figure a methylated histone h and hp are associated with silenced or heterochromatic regions of chromatin acetylated histone h is associated with actively expressed regions of chromatin histone h and condensin are not indicated in the figure because histone h is everywhere and condensin is only localized to chromosomes in mitosis not in interphase figure a  a creation of a pseudogene starts when a gene is duplicated next a random mutation inactivates or impairs one of the copies it is unlikely that the mutation has detrimental consequences for the cell or the organism because there is a second fully functional copy the mutated copy may continue to accumulate additional mutations without detrimental consequences and it may lose all functionality and perhaps even lose the ability to be expressed a nonfunctional gene is called a pseudogene b the simplest kind of experiment is a comparison of the expression patterns of the duplicated genes after duplication genes commonly diverge in their expression pattern the expectation then is that the mrna and the proteins encoded by the duplicated genes will be observed at different developmental stages or in different tissues or cell types or at different stages of the celldivision cycle or in different subcellular compartments c the answer to both questions is duplicated genes not singletons genes that are part of a duplicated or expanded set are more likely to exhibit more narrowly specialized expression duplicated genes that diverge are more likely to survive through evolutionary time because there will be detrimental consequences for loss of each gene one simple way to diverge such that both copies of a pair will be required is for random mutations of regulatory regions to generate differences in when and where each gene is turned on  a m and n diverged  million years ago b there is an average of  nucleotide substitution in m compared with n follow the path connecting the two species which is twice the distance between each one and their common ancestor c more however they show roughly the same degree of relatedness the sequence divergence between m and n is about  whereas that between p and s is about  m and n diverged  million years ago whereas p and s diverged  million years ago d it is more informative to compare species that are separated by a greater evolutionary distance comparing m and q which diverged  million years ago will therefore be better able to identify sequences likely to be important for function closely related species share many sequences by chance because insufficient time has passed for neutral mutations to accumulate  the simplest way to evolve the new gene is by duplication and divergence if the gene is duplicated then the cell or lineage can maintain one functional intact copy of the original gene and can thus tolerate a disabling mutation in the second copy the second copy can initially be modified by the x or y mutation that impairs its function at some later time many generations later the gene with the single mutation can acquire the additional mutation to yield the doubly mutant xy gene with the new or improved function reviews there are no reviews yet be the first to review “test bank for molecular biology of the cell th edition test bank – bruce alberts” cancel reply your email address will not be published required fields are marked your rating rate… perfect good average not that bad very poor your review name  email  notify me of new posts by email related products test bank for introductory mathematical analysis for business economics and the life and social sciences th edition test bank – haeussler  add to cart advanced accounting th edition – floyd a beams anthonybruce smith test bank  add to cart test bank for organizational behavior science the real world and you th edition test bank – nelson  add to cart search for we accept categoriesaccounting a