 called a pseudogene b the simplest kind of experiment is a comparison of the expression patterns of the duplicated genes after duplication genes commonly diverge in their expression pattern the expectation then is that the mrna and the proteins encoded by the duplicated genes will be observed at different developmental stages or in different tissues or cell types or at different stages of the celldivision cycle or in different subcellular compartments c the answer to both questions is duplicated genes not singletons genes that are part of a duplicated or expanded set are more likely to exhibit more narrowly specialized expression duplicated genes that diverge are more likely to survive through evolutionary time because there will be detrimental consequences for loss of each gene one simple way to diverge such that both copies of a pair will be required is for random mutations of regulatory regions to generate differences in when and where each gene is turned on  a m and n diverged  million years ago b there is an average of  nucleotide substitution in m compared with n follow the path connecting the two species which is twice the distance between each one and their common ancestor c more however they show roughly the same degree of relatedness the sequence divergence between m and n is about  whereas that between p and s is about  m and n diverged  million years ago whereas p and s diverged  million years ago d it is more informative to compare species that are separated by a greater evolutionary distance comparing m and q which diverged  million years ago will therefore be better able to identify sequences likely to be important for function closely related species share many sequences by chance because insufficient time has passed for neutral mutations to accumulate  the simplest way to evolve the new gene is by duplication and divergence if the gene is duplicated then the cell or lineage can maintain one functional intact copy of the original gene and can thus t